[
    {
        "content": "<p>On the nLab there is currently a number of discussions over whether the set of streams of a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is defined as the final coalgebra of the endofunctor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\mapsto A \\times X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> or the endofunctor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\mapsto 1 + A \\times X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/17554/list-of-notable-initial-algebras-and-terminal-coalgebras/#Item_0\">https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/17554/list-of-notable-initial-algebras-and-terminal-coalgebras/#Item_0</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/17572/stream/#Item_0\">https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/17572/stream/#Item_0</a></p>",
        "id": 409839546,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1703448859
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd say both deserve to be called \"streams\", but personally I'd assume <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\mapsto A\\times X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> unless you said otherwise. There's lots of work that uses that definition, e.g.  Rutten's work on \"stream calculus\".</p>",
        "id": 409886752,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathaniel Virgo",
        "timestamp": 1703491539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm far from being an expert, but now that I think about it, I have seen both definitions; usually I intend <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mo>−</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\times-</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span></span></span></span>, but Jacobs' coalgebra book (iirc) uses instead <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mo>−</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1+A\\times-</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span></span></span></span>...</p>",
        "id": 409901920,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1703502858
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In Glasgow the first are called streams and the latter colists</p>",
        "id": 410157903,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703685937
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would it be right to say that costreams are well defined, but that there aren't any?</p>",
        "id": 410302900,
        "sender_full_name": "Oscar Cunningham",
        "timestamp": 1703774450
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276945\">@Oscar Cunningham</span> what would be your intuitive definition of costream and why do you expect there not to be any?</p>",
        "id": 410409453,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703841638
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was checking my understanding of recursion and corecursion. The set of lists is defined as an initial algebra of the endofunctor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\mapsto 1+A×X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, which is the set of finite sequences valued in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> suggested using the term colist for the elements of the terminal coalgebra of this endofunctor; sequences of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> that are allowed to be finite or infinite.</p>\n<p>The set of streams is defined as the terminal coalgebra of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\mapsto A×X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, which is precisely the infinite sequences valued in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. So the set of costreams would be the initial algebra of this endofunctor. But I think this is just the empty set, since there's nothing like the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> in the endofunctor to force you to have any elements at all.</p>",
        "id": 410428989,
        "sender_full_name": "Oscar Cunningham",
        "timestamp": 1703853947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><em>Maybe</em> this argument works: on the category of Sets, or any other Cartesian closed category, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mo>−</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\times-</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span></span></span></span> commutes with colimits; its category of endofunctor algebras then has colimits and they are \"well-behaved\", so the initial object in the base (=the empty set) is created and becomes the initial object in the category of algebras, and also a fixpoint: so the initial costream is indeed the emtpy set.</p>",
        "id": 410431211,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1703855426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think there's any mathematical doubt here, the question is whether to adopt the nomenclature 'costreams' for such an object, I'd say it's technically OK but not very useful. Hence my <span aria-label=\"shrug\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f937\" role=\"img\" title=\"shrug\">:shrug:</span>:</p>",
        "id": 410432641,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703856484
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To me adding the co makes sense in the initial-&gt;terminal direction, not much conversely</p>",
        "id": 410432690,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703856530
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the rules are made up so <span aria-label=\"shrug\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f937\" role=\"img\" title=\"shrug\">:shrug:</span></p>",
        "id": 410432709,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703856544
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Definition.20of.20streams/near/410432690\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To me adding the co makes sense in the initial-&gt;terminal direction, not much conversely</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span aria-label=\"face with raised eyebrow\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f928\" role=\"img\" title=\"face with raised eyebrow\">:face_with_raised_eyebrow:</span> limits-&gt;colimits are in the converse direction</p>",
        "id": 410434358,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1703857743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They might be more interesting in other categories though.</p>",
        "id": 410434560,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703857910
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would expect costreams to be inhabited in the category of pointed sets for instance</p>",
        "id": 410445478,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenji Maillard",
        "timestamp": 1703864985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"284005\">Ralph Sarkis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Definition.20of.20streams/near/410434358\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Definition.20of.20streams/near/410432690\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To me adding the co makes sense in the initial-&gt;terminal direction, not much conversely</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span aria-label=\"face with raised eyebrow\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f928\" role=\"img\" title=\"face with raised eyebrow\">:face_with_raised_eyebrow:</span> limits-&gt;colimits are in the converse direction</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm talking about this specific terminological pattern (terminal algebras being named after the corresponding initial algebra)</p>",
        "id": 410447379,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1703866041
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This topic was moved here from <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"229136\" href=\"/#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Definition.20of.20streams\">#theory: category theory &gt; Definition of streams</a> by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span>.</p>",
        "id": 410447398,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1703866055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It would be nice if we could make a uniform choice of which side has the \"co\", but I don't think we can hope for that.</p>",
        "id": 410452414,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1703869003
    }
